==Demographics==
Clinton has a population of 905 as of the 2020 census. The employment rate is 70.2 percent, and approximately 44.1 percent of residents have a bachelor's degree or higher. 4.5 percent lack health insurance. The 461 families in the ZCTA are spread across 399 houses, which have a median household income of $89,086. The 4,071 residents of the ZCTA have a median age of 35.6, below Pennsylvania's median age of 40.9. The population is nearly all [[White people|white]] and are descended from Europe, with a plurality of them [[German Americans|descended from Germany]]. There are additionally, large sectors of [[English Americans]], [[Italian Americans]], [[Polish Americans]], and [[Irish Americans]]. In addition, there are  small minorities of [[French Americans]] and [[Scottish Americans]]. Only 3.7 percent of the population is foreign-born, all of whom are naturalized American citizens.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Clinton CDP, Pennsylvania, profile |url=https://data.census.gov/profile/Clinton_CDP,_Pennsylvania?g=160XX00US4214296 |access-date=2023-07-04 |website=data.census.gov}}</ref>

===Political affiliation===
In the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 presidential election]], Clinton and its nearby communities voted mostly for [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Donald Trump]] over [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Joe Biden]]. The margin in support of Trump was 28 percentage points, though the area supported Biden slightly more than [[Hillary Clinton]] in the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 election]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Park |first=Alice |last2=Smart |first2=Charlie |last3=Taylor |first3=Rumsey |last4=Watkins |first4=Miles |date=2021-02-02 |title=An Extremely Detailed Map of the 2020 Election |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2021/upshot/2020-election-map.html |access-date=2023-07-04 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>{{US Census population
